Iris dataset

Qualitative Visualizations
Bar Chart
Bar charts are used to compare categories of data.

Example:

unique, counts = np.unique(y, return_counts=True)
plt.bar(target_names, counts)
plt.title('Bar Plot of Iris Species')
plt.xlabel('Species')
plt.ylabel('Count')
Interpretation
The bar chart shows the frequency of each Iris species in the dataset.

Pie Chart
Pie charts display the proportion of categories in a dataset.

Example:

plt.pie(np.bincount(y), labels=target_names, autopct='%1.1f%%')
plt.title('Pie Plot of Iris Species')
Interpretation
Each slice represents the percentage of each species in the Iris dataset.

Quantitative Visualizations
Heatmap (Correlation Matrix)
Heatmaps visualize relationships between variables.

Example:

corr_matrix = np.corrcoef(X.T)
plt.imshow(corr_matrix, cmap='coolwarm')
Interpretation
The heatmap shows correlations between features such as:

sepal length

sepal width

petal length

petal width

Line Plot
Line plots are used to show trends across ordered data.

Example:

plt.plot(X[:, 0])
plt.xlabel('Sample Index')
plt.ylabel('Sepal Length (cm)')
plt.title('Line Plot of Sepal Length')
Interpretation
The plot shows how sepal length changes across observations.

Scatter Plot
Scatter plots show relationships between two continuous variables.

Example:

plt.scatter(X[y == i, 0], X[y == i, 1])
Interpretation
The scatter plot shows the relationship between:

sepal length

sepal width

Different colors represent different Iris species.

Box Plot
Box plots summarize the distribution of a dataset.

They show:

median

quartiles

outliers

Interpretation
The box plot visualizes the distribution of petal length for each Iris species.

Violin Plot
Violin plots provide a more detailed distribution view compared to box plots.

Interpretation
The violin plot shows the density distribution of petal width across species.

Histogram
Histograms show the distribution of numerical data.

Example:

plt.hist(X[:, 0], bins=20)
plt.title('Histogram of Sepal Length')
Interpretation
The histogram shows the frequency distribution of sepal length values.

